04384nam a22006495i 9781400890439DE-B159720210927121507.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210927t20182018nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008904397 a10.23943/97814008904392doi  a(DE-B1597)501151  a(OCoLC)1031968127  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a709.3942231 aNorth, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhat Is the Present? :bA History of the Here and Now /cMichael North. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b2 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- tPART ONE -- t1. This Point in Time -- t2. The Search for the Experiential Present -- t3. The Longest Now: A History of the Historical Present -- tPART TWO -- t4. The Present in Pictures -- t5. Narrative and the "Unexplained Instant" -- t6. The Cinematic Present from Intolerance to Interstellar -- tConclusion: Here and Now -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA provocative new look at concepts of the present, their connection to ideas about time, and their effect on literature, art, and cultureThe problem of the present-what it is and what it means-is one that has vexed generations of thinkers and artists. Because modernity places so much value on the present, many critics argue that people today spend far too much time in the here and now-but how can we tell without first knowing what the here and now actually is? What Is the Present? takes a provocative new look at this moment in time that remains a mystery even though it is always with us.Michael North tackles puzzles that have preoccupied philosophy, neuroscience, psychology, history, and aesthetic theory and examines the complex role of the present in painting, fiction, and film. He engages with a range of thinkers, from Aristotle and Augustine to William James and Henri Bergson. He draws illuminating examples from artists such as Fra Angelico and Richard McGuire, filmmakers like D. W. Griffith and Christopher Nolan, and novelists such as Elizabeth Bowen and Willa Cather. North offers a critical analysis of previous models of the present, from the experiential present to the historical period we call the contemporary. He argues that the present is not a cosmological or experiential fact but a metaphor, a figurative relationship with the whole of time. Presenting an entirely new conception of the temporal mystery Georg Lukács called the "unexplained instant," What Is the Present? explores how the arts have traditionally represented the present-and also how artists have offered radical alternatives to that tradition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aTime and art. 0aTime in art. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060659140uhttps://doi.org/10.23943/9781400890439zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400890439423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781400890439/original  a978-3-11-060659-1  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK